# 🌳 Symmetric Tree

> A tree is symmetric if its left and right subtrees are mirror images of each other.

---

## 🧠 Concept

This problem is based on **recursion + mirror comparison**.

Instead of checking one tree, we compare:

* Left subtree of one side
* Right subtree of the other side

👉 Basically: **mirror check (left ↔ right)**

---

## ⚙️ Approach

👉 If both nodes are null → return true
👉 If one is null → return false
👉 If values are different → return false

👉 Recursively check:

* left of first with right of second
* right of first with left of second

👉 Start by comparing:

* root.left with root.right

---

## 💻 Code (Java)

```java id="sym123"
class Solution {

    public static boolean symmetric(TreeNode n1, TreeNode n2)
    {
        if(n1 == null && n2 == null)
        {
            return true;
        }
        else if(n1 == null || n2 == null)
        {
            return false;
        }
        else if(n1.val != n2.val)
        {
            return false;
        }

        return symmetric(n1.left, n2.right) && symmetric(n1.right, n2.left);
    }

    public boolean isSymmetric(TreeNode root) {
        if(root == null)
        {
            return true;
        }
        return symmetric(root.left, root.right);
    }
}
```

---

## ⏱️ Complexity

* Time: O(n) → visit each node once
* Space: O(h) → recursion stack

---

## ❗ Mistakes / Learnings

* Don’t compare left with left → compare **left with right**
* Structure AND values must match
* Base case handling is very important

---

## 🔑 Key Insight

👉 Symmetry = **mirror comparison**, not normal traversal
